      "updated": 1784184263316,
      "link": null,
      "locked": false,
      "text": "We To solve the problem we did exactly as said & made a hashmap of the key value pairs and updated\nthe value everytime we encountered the same key again. and stored it if it was first used getOrDefault\nThen challenge was to find the top k elements for this we required bucket sort or priority queue\nbecause Hashmap is unordered we can't sort it using Comparator like i did with sorting my custom \nobject with Comparator. We used the fact that any element in an array can appear a maximum of the length of \nthe array number of times. so we create an array that is sparce that has indices upto n, and at each index\nthere is an arraylist or linked list that can stores all the elements that correspond to the frequency that equals\nthe index they are at.",
      "fontSize": 28,
      "fontFamily": 5,
      "textAlign": "left",
      "verticalAlign": "top",
      "containerId": null,
      "originalText": "We To solve the problem we did exactly as said & made a hashmap of the key value pairs and updated\nthe value everytime we encountered the same key again. and stored it if it was first used getOrDefault\nThen challenge was to find the top k elements for this we required bucket sort or priority queue\nbecause Hashmap is unordered we can't sort it using Comparator like i did with sorting my custom \nobject with Comparator. We used the fact that any element in an array can appear a maximum of the length of \nthe array number of times. so we create an array that is sparce that has indices upto n, and at each index\nthere is an arraylist or linked list that can stores all the elements that correspond to the frequency that equals\nthe index they are at.",
